prehistory? -- tOn the structure of caverns and architecture -- tFreedom of approach to all surfaces -- tThe coming change -- tPrehistoric space conception and contemporary art -- tThe eternal present -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tLIST OF WORKS CITED -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA groundbreaking reevaluation of paleolithic art through the lens of modernism, from the acclaimed historian of art and architectureIn The Beginnings of Art, Sigfried Giedion, best known as a historian of architecture, shifts his attention to art and its very origins. Breaking with an earlier, materialistic approach, he explores paleolithic art by bringing abstraction, transparency, and simultaneity into play as modern art has revealed them anew. Focusing on the dual concepts of constancy and change, he examines paleolithic paintings, engravings, and sculpture, as well as modern art and recent examples of “primitive art.” He argues that the two keys to the meaning of prehistoric art are the symbol, portraying reality before reality exists, and the animal as humankind’s superior in the unified primordial world in which both human and animal were embedded. The result is a highly original and important study of prehistoric art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aArt, Prehistoric. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh  aAlexander the Great.  aFrazer, J. G.  aGillen, F. J.  aHinduism.  aITHYPHALLIC REPRESENTATIONS.  aLuquet, G. H.  aLuxor.  aMin.  aPERFORATIONS.  aRead, Herbert.  aReinach, Salomon.  aSYMBOLS/symbolization/symbolism/symbolic forms.  aSaint-Germain-en-Laye, museum.  aSpencer, B.  aStatius.  aVenus figurines/statuettes.  aWorringer, Wilhelm.  aadornment, desire for.  aand origin of art.  aand purpose of a